(25, 'en_US', 'abstract', 'The aim of this study is to examine the effect of gender and hazardous situation on risk perception and risky riding behavior among motorcyclists. Seventy two participants were asked to read scenarios and watch six video clips that show the pro-risk and anti-risk hazardous situation. At the end of each clip, participants answer some questions related to risk perception and lane-splitting decision. The result shows that hazardous situation has a significant effect on risk perception, in total and also for each dimension, and lane-splitting behavior. The gender only has a significant effect on two dimensions of risk perception, which are efficacy and worry &amp; insecurity. We also found a significant interaction between hazardous situation and gender on the likelihood of accident dimension. Based on the results of this study, it is important for the law enforcer to consider the role of risk perception in the process of riding license.', 'string'),
