(38, 'en_US', 'abstract', 'We examined law enforcement officersâ€™ knowledge about memory. To do so, we performed two levels of analysis. First we compared memory-related knowledge and erroneous beliefs of officers (<em>n</em> = 200) and lay people (<em>n</em> = 403) and found similar low scores of knowledge between these two groups, and a higher amount of erroneous beliefs among the law enforcement officers. Second, we compared knowledge and erroneous beliefs of officers who followed training in investigative interview (<em>n</em> = 41) to those of their untrained counterparts (<em>n</em> = 159). Similar low scores in knowledge and false beliefs were found. However, when comparing officers who conduct five interviews or more per month (<em>n</em> = 82) to officers who conduct zero interviews per month (<em>n</em> = 43), we found that the first group expressed more erroneous beliefs. The results are discussed in line with previous research, in particular those on investigative interview practices.', 'string'),
