(21, 'en_US', 27, 1, 9, 'en', '<p>Â </p><p>Professor Sri Hartati R-Suradijono, M.A., Ph.D</p><p>Faculty of Psychology</p><p>Universitas Indonesia</p><p>Depok - West Java, 16424</p><p align="center">Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â </p><p align="right"><strong>Depok, 22<sup>nd</sup> of February 2018</strong></p><p align="center"><strong>Â </strong></p><p align="center"><strong>COVER LETTER</strong></p><p>Dear Professor Suradijono,</p><p>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  We are pleased to submit our manuscript <em>â€œDifferences on Psychotic Experiences, Depressive Symptoms, Anxiety Symptoms and Common Mental Health Risk Factors on Urban and Non-Urban Dwellers in Indonesia</em><em>â€ </em>as an original research article for publication in Psychological Research on Urban Society (PRoUSt). The manuscript consists of 3970 words with one table.</p><p>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  The study examines differences between urban and non-urban dwellers on the prevalence of mental health symptoms and common mental health risk factors. Specifically, we investigate the differences in terms of psychotic experiences, depressive symptoms, and anxiety symptoms as well as loneliness, bullying victim experience, child abuse experience, and negative schema. Our findings have important implications for investigations of candidate mechanisms underlying the association between urbanicity and mental health problem. Moreover, our findings suggest the importance of promoting prevention and awareness program in the urban area.</p><p>Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â Â  We confirm that the study meets the ethical guidelines and adheres to the legal requirements of the research country. No potential conflict of interest is associated with the manuscript. It has not been previously published and is not currently submitted for publication elsewhere. The names of all co-authors have been included in the manuscript. All authors have had an active part in the final manuscript and confirm their agreement to submission.</p><p class="LetterBody">Â </p><p class="LetterBodyCxSpLast">With kind regards,</p><p class="LetterClosingCxSpFirst">Edo S. Jaya</p><p class="LetterClosingCxSpLast">On behalf of all authors</p>', 'Breslau, J., Marshall, G. N., Pincus, H. A., & Brown, R. A. (2014). Are mental disorders more common in urban than rural areas of the United States? Journal of Psychiatric Research, 56, 50-55. 10.1016/j.jpsychires.2014.05.004 [doi] \r\n\r\nBuhrmester, M., Kwang, T., & Gosling, S. D. (2011). Amazon''s Mechanical Turk: A new source of inexpensive, yet high-quality, data? Perspect Psychol Sci, 6(1), 3-5. 10.1177/1745691610393980 \r\n\r\nCoid, J. W., Hu, J., Kallis, C., Ping, Y., Zhang, J., Hu, Y., . . . Kirkbride, J. B. (2017). Urban birth, urban living, and work migrancy: Differential effects on psychotic experiences among young Chinese men. Schizophrenia Bulletin, 10.1093/schbul/sbx152 [doi] \r\n\r\nFowler, D., Freeman, D., Smith, B., Kuipers, E., Bebbington, P., Bashforth, H., . . . Garety, P. (2006). The brief core schema scales (BCSS): Psychometric properties and associations with paranoia and grandiosity in non-clinical and psychosis samples. Psychological Medicine, 36(6), 749-759. S0033291706007355 [pii] \r\n\r\nGruebner, O., A. Rapp, M., Adli, M., Kluge, U., Galea, S., & Heinz, A. (2017). Cities and mental health. Dtsch Arztebl Int, 114(8), 121-127. 10.3238/arztebl.2017.0121 [doi] \r\n\r\nHanssen, M., Krabbendam, L., Vollema, M., Delespaul, P., & van Os, J. (2006). Evidence for instrument and family-specific variation of subclinical psychosis dimensions in the general population. Journal of Abnormal Psychology, 115(1), 5-14. 2006-02317-002 [pii] \r\n\r\nJanssen, I., Krabbendam, L., Bak, M., Hanssen, M., Vollebergh, W., de Graaf, R., & van Os, J. (2004). Childhood abuse as a risk factor for psychotic experiences. Acta Psychiatrica Scandinavica, 109(1), 38-45. 217 [pii] \r\n\r\nJaya, E. S. (2017). Confirmatory factor analysis of the Indonesian ve