(130, 257, 21, 4, '2018-03-07 08:49:47', '202.62.16.147', NULL, '"Debora Eflina Purba" <eflina@gmail.com>', '"Dr. Edo Sebastian Jaya" <edo.jaya@ui.ac.id>', NULL, 'eflina@gmail.com', '[PRoUSt] Editorial letter on your manuscript', 'Dear Dr. E. S. Jaya,\r\n\r\nThank you for considering the Psychological Research on Urban Society as an outlet for your work.  I have now received an expert review of your manuscript entitled "Psychotic Experiences, Depressive Symptoms, Anxiety Symptoms and Common Mental Health Risk Factors of Urban and Non-Urban Dwellers in Indonesia," and I have also read the manuscript independently of the reviewer comments. Both the reviewer and I agree that the topic is important and fit-in well with our journal theme. However, I agree with the reviewer that the manuscript still needs to be revised to improve its readability, which in my opinion can be easily done by making clear concept definitions that you use in your manuscript and making small corrections as suggested by the reviewer. I include reviewersâ€™ comments on the manuscript for your consideration. \r\n\r\nRegarding suggestion no. 5 from the reviewer, if it is not possible for you to rerun the test by controlling demographic variables, I suggest that you mention this in the future direction of the study. Having said this, I also suggest that you soften your tone in your conclusion of the difference between urban and rural dwellers. Please be sure to include a point-by-point response to each of the issues raised by the reviewer.\r\n\r\nTo submit a revision, please login with your account http://proust.ui.ac.id with your username and password. If you have any problem regarding this step, please email us at proust@ui.ac.id.\r\n\r\nAs your manuscript needs a minor revision, I would like to receive the revision within ten days from the receipt of this letter. Please let me know if you would like to have additional time.\r\n\r\nYours sincerely,\r\n\r\nDebora Eflina Purba\r\nEditor\r\nPsychological Research on Urban Society\r\n\r\nReviewers'' comments:\r\n\r\nThis manuscript explores the prevalence of common risk factors and symptoms of mental health between the urban and non-urban inhabitants in Indonesia. The authors found that respondents living in the urban area had higher scores in the risk factors: loneliness, bullying at home, and negative schema, and mental disorder symptoms: positive symptom and depression. Therefore, they conclude that living in urban might linked to higher exposure to mental health risk factor and more possible to have mental health problems. This manuscript is well-written but, in my opinion, incomplete. See below for some comments and questions:   \r\n1)	Please provide page number to help the reviewers address specific comment/issue in the manuscript\r\n2)	2.1. Participants and procedure: The definition of urban and non-urban in this study was not clearly defined. In the limitation section of discussion, the author mentioned about â€œin this study, urbanicity was conceptualized as the current place of residence.â€ How was the current place of residence judged as urban or non-urban: government administration definition, respondent self-judged, etc?  \r\n3)	Results â€“ Participant characteristics: Itâ€™s better to provide a table of demographic characteristics of the participants. This will help the readers to understand easier the sample and level of representativeness. How many of this study sample was urban and non-urban? Some of the sentences in this part are not clear enough, for example: (i) Participants were significantly different in terms of age (t(680.460) = -4.11, p < .01), income (t(830) = -2.49, p < .05), education (U = 96,316.500, p < .01), and SES (U = 93,813.00, p < .05).. which participants was refereed in this result? (ii) which measures were being referred to â€œâ€¦ with non-urban participants showing higher mean scores across measures than urban participantsâ€? \r\n4)	4.1. Main findings: â€œParticipants living in the non-urban area were significantly older, had a higher level of income, education, as well as socio-economic status.â€ I find this as strange and unlikely! Could you elaborate more on this? \r\n5)	3.2. Urban and non-urban differences: t-tests or Mann-Whitney U test was applied comparing each variable between the two groups. Would it better if this comparison is also controlling for sociodemographic factors; i.e., gender, education, SES since the two samples were significantly different regarding sociodemographic factors? Furthermore, the authors have the risk factors, groups (urban vs. non-urban), and the symptoms of mental disorders: why not model them and see whether the place of residence plays a significant role? \r\n6)	3.2. Urban and non-urban differences: The significant differences between urban and non-urban found in this study should be seen in the light of the statistical power of almost 1000 respondents. As can be seen, all the significant differences effect sizes were small: 0.14-0.25. This should be mentioned in the result and discussion section. \r\n7)	Limitation: The possibility of access to the internet, hence to enroll n this study, is higher in an urban area than rural. Would this be considered as a possible bias? \r\n8)	Conclusion: In my opinion, the conclusion of â€œliving in an urban environment is one risk factor contributing to a poorer mental health conditionâ€ is too strong considering the simple descriptive analysis as conducted in the present manuscript.\n________________________________________________________________________\r\nPsychological Research on Urban Society (PRoUSt)\r\nhttp://proust.ui.ac.id/'),
