(25, 55, 'string', 'I personally question the adequacy of the methodology. The intervention was done only in 3 days with 2 materials in one day, making it seemed like the author was in a rush to complete the study and did not plan the study thoroughly. I believe that children with ID need more time to learn new skills and repetitions are very much important (as the author also stated). Even if the author observed an increase in % of skill acquirement , the author did not do follow ups to ensure the skills were maintained (such increase may be the result of intense sessions and the acquired skills may be lost once the sessions ended and no reinforcement/repetitions were given). Therefore, I lean toward rejecting the paper if the author could not provide strong arguments for why intervention were conducted only in 3 days with 2 materials packed into one session as well as why follow ups were not conducted.'),
(26, 55, 'string', 'There are some important details that were not included in the article, e.g., example of measurement items, duration of each session, why only 3 days, why two materials were covered in one session (did the author consider the fact that children with ID need more time to learn?), what kind of questions/measurements given to assess mastery of skill in the beginning of each session, what was the indicator that the subject had mastered the skill taught in previous session. Also, it was not clear if the three sessions were conducted in three consecutive days.  \r\n\r\nThe author made a strong conclusion that the program was effective to improve the subject''s safety skills; however, there was no follow up while the author already stated that repetition is required and encouraged parents to get involved in continuing the program. Therefore, I believe that follow ups are needed to ensure that the skills are not lost and maintained for longer period of time. Several follow ups in a span of at least 6 months are needed to observe the behaviour/skill acquirement and maintenance, Follow ups can also further support the study''s findings and conclusion that the intervention program was indeed effective for that subject to develop safety skills.'),
